    <!-- Content Sections -->
    <div class="content-section">
        <section id="Bhatye Beach" class="section">
            <h2>Bhatye Beach</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,">
            <p>Bhatye Beach, located in Ratnagiri, Maharashtra, is a long, flat, and straight beach known for its gentle waves, scenic views, and opportunities for various activities. It's a popular spot for locals and tourists alike, offering a relaxing atmosphere for walks, sunset views, and beach games. </p>
            <p>Flat and Straight:The beach is known for its flat, straight stretch, making it ideal for leisurely walks and relaxation.Scenic Views:Bhatye Beach offers beautiful views of the Arabian Sea, especially during sunrise and sunset.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="Mandavi Beach" class="section">
            <h2>Mandavi Beach</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Mandavi Beach" class="section-image">
            <p>Mandvi Beach, located in Gujarat's Kutch district, is a popular destination known for its expansive sandy shoreline, clear waters, and tranquil atmosphere. It's a place to enjoy picturesque sunsets, relax on the beach, and engage in activities like camel rides, horseback riding, and water sports. The beach is also known for the historic Mandvi port and the surrounding wind turbines, which add to its scenic beauty. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Marine Aquarium & Museum" class="section">
            <h2>Marine Aquarium & Museum</h2>
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSEw6P_j7um5tYAbhu3ksEFbTL4bson2oE-Hg&s" alt="Marine Aquarium & Museum" class="section-image">
            <p>The Ratnagiri Marine Fish Museum, also known as the Marine Aquarium and Museum, offers a glimpse into the diverse marine life of the Arabian Sea and the history of Ratnagiri's fishing culture</p>
            <p>The museum is located at 272P+FG7, Sadanand Wadi, Ratnagiri, Maharashtra 415612, India.It's situated near the Ratnadurga Fort.It is located approximately 2.5 km from the Ratnagiri Bus Stand and 9.5 km from the Ratnagiri Railway Station. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Thiba (Thibaw) Palace & Thibaw Point" class="section">
            <h2>Thiba (Thibaw) Palace & Thibaw Point</h2>
            <img src="http://t3.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSNs29als0PdUaOr3a9NPEZ_ZDvgdAyM7FwZeXGibJZ6UNEJFG6JUiGmFm9TV30SREBApSVSi4W" alt="Thiba (Thibaw) Palace & Thibaw Point" class="section-image">
            <p>Thiba Palace, located in Ratnagiri, Maharashtra, is a significant historical site built in 1910 by the British government for King Thibaw (also known as King Thabba Min), the last king of Burma (now Myanmar), during his exile in India. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Ratnadurg Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Ratnadurg Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ratnadurg Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Ratnadurg Fort, also known as Bhagwati Fort, is a historical fort located in Ratnagiri, Maharashtra, overlooking the Arabian Sea. It was built during the Bahamani Sultanate period and later conquered by Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj in 1670. The fort is horseshoe-shaped and spans 120 acres, serving as a strategic vantage point for the Maratha Empire. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Ganeshgule Beach & Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Ganeshgule Beach & Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ganeshgule Beach & Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>Ganeshgule is a serene coastal village in Ratnagiri, Maharashtra, known for its beautiful beach and ancient Ganesha temple. The beach is a secluded 1km stretch of white sand and azure waters, perfect for relaxation and enjoying water sports like snorkeling and diving. The nearby temple, also named Ganeshgule, is an ancient structure made of laterite stone, believed to be over 400 years old. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Ganpatipule" class="section">
            <h2>Ganpatipule</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ganpatipule" class="section-image">
            <p>Ganpatipule is a town located in the Ratnagiri district of Maharashtra, India, known for its coastal beauty and the Ganpati temple. It's a popular pilgrimage and tourist destination, attracting visitors with its serene beach and religious significance. The temple, dedicated to Lord Ganesha, is believed to be "swayambhu" (self-originated). </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Panhalakaji Caves" class="section">
            <h2>Panhalakaji Caves</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Panhalakaji Caves" class="section-image">
            <p>Panhalakaji Caves, located in Ratnagiri district, Maharashtra, is a complex of 30 Buddhist caves carved into the hillsides. These caves, primarily dating back to the 3rd century AD, showcase a blend of Buddhist sects and later Hindu influences. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Jaigad Fort & Lighthouse" class="section">
            <h2>Jaigad Fort & Lighthouse</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Jaigad Fort & Lighthouse" class="section-image">
            <p>Jaigad Fort and Lighthouse are two prominent attractions in Jaigad, a coastal village in Ratnagiri, Maharashtra. Jaigad Fort, a 16th-century sea fort built by the Bijapur Sultanate, offers historical insights and scenic views, while the Jaigad Lighthouse, a British-built structure from 1932, provides stunning coastal vistas, especially during its limited visiting hours. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Purnagad Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Purnagad Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Purnagad Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Purnagad Fort is a small, restored fort located 25 km from Ratnagiri city in Maharashtra, India. It's known for its historical significance as a base for Kanhoji Angre's navy and its beautiful views of the Arabian Sea and Muchkundi River. The fort is relatively small but well-maintained and offers a good spot for photography. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
